I was only diagnosed in my legs but I‚Äôm scared it‚Äôs spreading. I feel so scared and worried. I‚Äôm only 30.

New to the group. I recently got diagnosed with alcoholic neuropathy. Something I did to myself and obviously regret it. Started out in my hands and the feet and legs. I‚Äôve since quit drinking of course. Hands are just a little tingly, however feet are a different story. It‚Äôs just agonizing pain. Not hot, sensitive to touch and horrible inside ankle pain, and toes are horrible at night. Strong sharp shooting pain. Doctors have told me that my type is possibly reversible if treated accordingly.  I‚Äôve read some of the post on here and I‚Äôm saddened that the Gabapentin has not worked that well. The doctor gave me a low dose of Cymbalta. Which will treat the pain better?

Hey guys, I have a basic question some of you may know the answer to. If you overdose on a substance and caused nerve damage, would your symptoms come and go or be more or less constant?  Like, can you go 24 hrs (sleep well and have no symptoms the next day) and then the following night for the numbness and tingling sensation to come back (which starts in the hands and arm/s and travels throughout the body over night messing with sleep and making you feel sore with like full-body neuropathy the next day to some extent. Then for this to ware off and get better for another 24rs and worse again?  I think I do notice that even on good nights I may feel at least some tingling in my hand/s and arm/s when I lay down for bed, but it may or may not flare and lead to an attack of sort of like parasthesia.  I also have Lyme disease which could explain the symptoms, along with some anxiety even, but this all followed a nutmeg overdose and all three mess with the nervous system. Does it sound like permanent nerve damage?

Thank you for the add! I am 18 years now living with chronic abdominal pain. It has been said several times that it is neuropathy or nerve entrapment syndrome. I‚Äôve recently had GI work up and have ruled out GI and autoimmune conditions. I don‚Äôt have a Neurologist and have not seen one for this pain. The only meds that take it away completely is Prednisone and tramadol helps a little. I‚Äôve tried multiple nerve pain meds with no success. I do have a syrinx at T7 and I am waiting on my first visit with the Neurosurgeon at this time. This pain started 6 mo after I had my gallbladder taken out in 2002. Nothing triggers it or sets it off and when I sleep I am pain free but the moment I wake up it‚Äôs horrible. I just requested an appointment at the Mayo Clinic because I dont know what else to do. I feel like no one around here wants to help me. Anyone in a similar situation as me?

Yesterday, I went to an EMG/NCS appointment at a workers comp- approved office. In fact it was a pain management clinic. I'd read that both tests together could take anywhere from 45 minutes to a couple of hours.  The entire appt from the moment I entered the building to when I walked out the door took 25 minutes and then she diagnosed tendonitis of the elbow, which is absurd as the symptoms aren't even the same.  I'm requesting a second opinion, but I'm wondering what your experience with the tests were? I actually have bilateral neuropathy in the arms. No known cause yet.

anybody have autonomic PN? It feels like an elephant is sitting on my chest; can't breathe well or sleep. any tips, ideas. Also, just found out the right side of my heart doesn't pump all the blood out. I have a; right branch bundle block, Stage 2 hypertension disease, risk group 3, left ventricular hypertrophy, IHD: diffuse cardiosclerosis, Grade 1 atrioventricular block, calcified heart disease, Grade 1 atrioventricular block, Calcifying heart disease, Grade 1 heart failure, with preserved LV systolic function.
I just recently Have been confirmed to have Neuropathy after months of doctors telling me it was something else. I‚Äôm new to this and I‚Äôm not going to lie, some of these posts are terrifying.

Tomorrow I return to having 2  60 minute hyper baric oxygen sessions.............hoping to help anything connected to diabetes which hits the human body in every way possible. My feet are feeling really good now I think due to this medical procedure (which should be covered by insurance, but usually it is not), because I think my feet are actually healthier with improved circulation it's no wonder. And it also seems to last, I havent had this procedure for about 4 months now and if my feet remain as they are - I can live very comfortably without pain killers. I used to be very uncomfortable, I couldnt take a shower the water hitting my feet was unbearable, I had to wear socks at night, now I dont. The tingles and burning and shooting pain have been reduced to a tiny roar. Do I still have neuropathy? you bet I do. I know it there due to a low level of numbness. But I can feel everything, my feet are warm and pink. They used to be cold, irritated, and I suffered from dry skin in the Winter. Now I dont.  So the neuropathy  seems to be either well controlled, extremely marginalized, or actually getting better... and, yes, I consider it to be a miracle. Ill have 2  60 minute sessions one tomorrow and one on Thursday. I will be walking on air. I want all of you here to be feeling better, able to rest, be pain free, etc. Ill share an article about the use of hyper baric oxygen therapy as soon as I get the link or a copy of the article. Best wishes! Bonny Cooper

My Rheumatologist had given me a prescription for Lidocaine cream but my insurance wouldn't cover it bc they said you can buy it over the counter. They didn't take in consideration the strength. So my great doctor is calling in an ointment instead bc they will pay for that. I personally think an ointment of lidocaine would be even better. So if you come up with the same problem try the ointment instead. Hope this helps you guys.
